{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01B5mLV3saiWpZAVFwYdY2xc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"All 785 tests pass. Now I need to write new Vitest tests to cover the gaps from issue #944:\n\n1. `computeTrialStatus` pure unit tests (edge cases at the 30-day boundary)\n2. `initTrial` Redis key/TTL unit tests\n3. `getTrial` malformed JSON handling\n\nLet me create a `trial-store.test.ts` file. I'll keep it within the 5-test budget for a small fix. But let me look more carefully at what's needed.\n\nThe key acceptance criteria for #944:\n- AC1: New Google sign-in starts a trial (keepalive: true fix)\n\n\n- AC2: Even if keepalive fails, auto-init on status check\n- AC3: Canceled Stripe customers can still start a trial (no Stripe status check in trial flow)\n\nFiremanDecko has covered AC2 and AC3 in his trial-status-route tests. What's genuinely untested is the boundary behavior in `computeTrialStatus` around day 30, the TTL constant in `initTrial`, and how `getTrial` handles malformed JSON responses.\n\nI need exactly 5 tests to cover these gaps: checking null input, the 30-day expiration boundary, the 29-day active state, converted trials regardless of elapsed time, and verifying that `initTrial` sets the correct Redis key and TTL. I'll create a new test file specifically for `trial-store.ts` to isolate these unit tests from the route-level coverage.\n\nFor the auth callback and Redis key logic mentioned in the requirements, the route tests already validate the keepalive behavior and cache clearing, so I'll focus my unit tests on the core `computeTrialStatus` logic and the auto-init defense-in-depth behavior that matters for issue #944—specifically that when no trial exists at status check time, the system creates one automatically.\n\nWriting focused unit tests for trial-store...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":